            "highlights": [
                {
                    "text": "intransigence",
                    "date": "2025-07-11T03:42:42.228"
                },
                {
                    "text": "Being a mother was what defined her more than any other thing—more than being a daughter, wife, divorced woman, girlfriend, or restaurant owner",
                    "date": "2025-07-21T06:20:12.124"
                },
                {
                    "text": "There were so many errors. If life allowed revisions, she would let them stay in their bath a little longer, read them one more story before bed, and fix them another plate of shrimp.",
                    "date": "2025-07-21T06:22:10.822"
                },
                {
                    "text": "Etsuko had failed in this important way—she had not taught her children to hope, to believe in the perhaps-absurd possibility that they might win. Pachinko was a foolish game, but life was not.",
                    "date": "2025-07-21T06:26:23.972"
                },
                {
                    "text": "Somewhere after being sorry, there had to be another day, and even after a conviction, there could be good in the judgment",
                    "date": "2025-07-21T06:30:24.699"
                }
            ]
        },
